rComments: Taking this class was a great experience.  It changed my relationship to poetry.  One of the better classes I've had at UofT.

Articulate, intelligent, discerning. Challenges prejudices and stereotypical thinking. Probably the most intimidating professor at U of T. Sometimes I felt that I should "bow in the presence of [his] greatness." Reminds me of Sid Poitier in To Sir, With Love. Yes, I did have a crush on him, but mostly because he was such a brilliant thinker.

I think his choices for the syllabus were diverse and relevant. However, the reasons behind why he would agree with some statements and dismiss others in class discussions were often unclear, as were explanations of the significance of certain concepts. The vibe of the class was a bit elitist and contemptuous towards those who were confused.

Has no interest in supporting students who are struggling with the materiel and would rather give disciplinary lectures on the proper way to address him: "Professor Campbell". His choices on poets don't make much sense for his demographic and fall on deaf ears. Hip hop is not poetry, Professor Campbell.

Most 'lectures' were too loose and informal, and almost always driven by student discussion. It seemed like a student's comment could change the whole direction of that class. Some interesting conclusions were drawn from the texts, but it often took very long to get there.
Good to great professor. Approachable, enthusiastic, fair. I don't much like his syllabus, but I like his humor. Its an even trade-off.
